an to undermine CSD2's new mechanics:  The introduction of holding stations is brilliant and adds unprecedented depth to your gameplay.  CSD1 focused on simply maximizing buzz and getting perfect orders, but trying to serve side dishes and drinks with every meal, being able to prep dishes ahead of time and needing to deal with dishes getting stale is a HUGE advancement in terms of depth.  However, as much as the game has advanced in these regards, it has regressed in the cooking of food, which I'd argue should be the focus.  Every dish has a delicious exterior (and a hilarious description to boot) but making them can often feel monotonous and samey, no matter how exotic the origin.\n\nThe game is also missing much of the miscellaneous gameplay and alternative modes from the previous.  There aren't concrete objectives available to upgrade your restaurant, there's no cooking challenges available, the health inspector is nowhere to be seen nor are the weather mechanics (if they're still in, that's a fault on both the tutorials, the e-mail system and the boosters/detractors not being fully complete), and robberies actually just feel like another chore now.  I will concede the robberies are a trade-off of variety for balance;  In the previous game, having to deal with one usually meant you lost a perfect day, here it's just another chore.  Ironically, having to deal with your robber directly is less threatening than losing customers to him was in the previous.\n\n[strike]The UI in its current state leaves much to be desired, ...[/strike] A recent patch has added a notice to distinguish chef-for-hire from your own custom restaurant before you start, and suggests you check out the tutorial.  This alleviates most of my initial concerns, with the rest of the UI bugs fixed and remaining features added in (e-mails in particular) it should prove pretty servicable.\n\nI'm unable to rate the balance of food bosters/detractors yet as that feature is currently hidden, but I guarantee you making them visible won't make the catalog much easier to approach without a better way to sift through it.  You absolutely need more ways to filter the foods, whether through individual boosters/detractors (simplying sorting by those would be another headache in itself), origin/culture (which doesn't make any sense gameplay-wise), or otherwise.\n\nIn it's current state, I'm afraid I have to give this a thumbs down.  A \"mixed\" rating would be more appropriate but steam reviews don't allow for that sort of nuance.\nI know I went on a lot about the reduced complexity of creating individual dishes, but the additional mechanics of sides and holding stations bring a huge amount more to the table.  The tipping point for me between a positive and a negative is the intuitive design the game currently lacks;  Fix those bugs, make it more user friendly and you've got a thumbs up.\n\nBest of luck with the continued development!", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505367006, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1505982517, "recommendationid": "34942799", "language": "english", "votes_down": 58, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.723272", "voted_up": false}, {"author": {"last_played": 1505671388, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 22, "playtime_forever": 234, "steamid": "76561198041620963", "num_games_owned": 290}, "votes_funny": 2, "votes_up": 112, "comment_count": "8", "review": "This game is good, and it almost feels wrong to not recommend it, but a lot of what made the first Cook, Serve, Delicious! feel so right and so good is currently gone. Some of it has yet to be added, for sure, but some of it seems to just plain be missing. I will avoid talking too much about what's currently missing, as I trust the developer for sticking to his promise of adding these features soon.\n\nThe first and probably biggest problem I personally have with this game is that there's no real progression. You are introduced to new foods at a rapid pace, and barely get any time to get used to them before already being shoved onto the next set of foods. Rather than having a small set of foods that you upgrade to slowly introduce more elements to them like in the first one, you get to buy a massive amount of foods for your own restaurant that have all of the options unlocked from the begin. This doesn't really make me want to use the foods, it feels like after seeing every recipe card once you've already seen all there is to see of this food (which is both the case and not encouraging to use said food more). The new Chef-For-Hire mode has a similar problem, but at least it makes more sense here. Where's the upgrades, both for food and the restaurant?\n\nThe second problem is related to the first problem I talked about, and the Chef For Hire mode. Now, I have nothing against this mode existing, in fact, I think this mode is a really good idea and I'm glad something like this is in the game. The problem for me is that it feels like the mode is what the game is focused on. Instead of working on your own restaurant, gradually unlocking upgrades as you go (which was really the thing that made the first game so good in my opinion), you just go from one place to another, making foods you likely haven't even been introduced to or have had practice for, only to get some money and a gold medal for that specific level.\nI feel like this mode needs to be secondary. Working on and upgrading your own restaurant is what the game should, at its core, really be about. It isn't, though. The game is at its core just making foods in other restaurants that you don't actually work on improving. Your own restaurant is as a result not really even upgrade-able. It feels like a side mode where you just practice on foods you unlocked instead of being an actually important thing in the game.\n\nThere's other problems I had with the game, for sure, but those were more minor than these two, and other negative reviews ha