 it feels like they were added to pad the number of menu options. Overall the system is a nice twist on the ticket system.\n\n[*]The addition of the restaurant designer lets you build your own restaurant background to look at while serving. It's a nice inclusion even though I'm not personally interested in the feature, I know there're people that will like it.\n\n[*]The music's still good, but I kinda prefer the music from CSD 1.\n[/list]\n\n[h1]The Bad:[/h1]\n[list]\n[*]The whole food preparation element of the game has gained tonnes of new food things to learn and add to your menu, at the cost of everything feeling kinda the same. In the original CSD each food felt like it's own beast, you had to learn a unique set of rules for everything, some of which were as simple as just remembering the \"cut fish\" buttons and others as fiddly as executing the exact order of a highly complex arrangement of sushi or waiting for a specific moment in the cooking process to add something else. Those things are still present in CSD 2 for a few of the menu options but because there are SO MANY ITEMS that all behave with the same mechanics (just add toppings to something) you don't really feel like each food has its own soul, instead it's sharing it with half the other menu options. The menu you constructed on a day-to-day basis in CSD 1 was a challenge of balancing complex to make foods and simple things that still felt interesting to prep, but the foods prep all feels kinda bland across so many of the menu options in CSD 2. Overall, less food options that were more interesting individually would definitely have been more.\n\n[*]Because a lot of the food options feel the same, and there are so many, most of the times I try to do a day of serving then I never really feel like I'm learning anything because I've got another 2 new things on the menu and they have another 10 buttons I'm meant to know just to cover the toppings that they have but don't share with other foods. I'm grappling to actually remember any of the food preps and that memory aspect is what makes you feel like you're getting a handle on the chaos. When rush hour starts I'm just desperately scrabbling through the three pages of toppings and I'm maxed out on orders so panicking about it all. I've definitely been that busy in CSD 1 but the fewer items meant you got a grip on them more and knew which items you could fulfil in a flash and get them off the queue to give you time to do more complex things. In CSD 2 there are some items that look very similar and while you don't have to include them on your menu together, they do mean you're basically learning each one again because they have enough variation between them to be the same to make mechanically (and thus a bit boring) but a pain to remember when you're doing different ones each day. If more foods felt more unique then you'd remember them better rather than just desperately scrabbling for a food that feels completely new every time.\n\n[*]The taking out of specific food upgrades combined with the huge menu really gimped the feeling of progression. The nice thing about CSD 1 was that you could buy a new menu item for your menu and give it a few run throughs when it only has a few toppings or processes to make. Then, when you get good at it, you upgrade it for more money per order but a higher complexity. That upgrade system let you gate the difficulty of foods while still making it meaningful to want to get up to the next level of difficulty when you felt competent enough. I get that the progression in this is meant to be about unlocking some of the other food type options but there are already an insane number of those as it is so it doesn't feel like a reward to get something I already have way too much to remember of. The other progression (unlocking new items to decorate your restaurant) is fair enough but doesn't feel like a reward/progression of your skills. \n\n[*]The change from the TV chef programs and challenge parties you had to do in CSD 1 to the \"Chef for Hire\" system was an attempt that had merit but overall I just prefer the original. The original system gave your chef a sense of prestige and progress as you attended increasingly more dramatic/important side games. Comparatively, the Chef for Hire system just feels like a huge slog of endlessly preparing the same things for different restaurants to unlock some menu things and decorative items for your restaurant. I like the idea but the execution fell flat for me.\n\n[*]Small point but while the font rendering was patched recently, it still looks kinda horrid to me. Furthermore, I actually preferred CSD 1's art style and dislike this one's a lot more but that's both a comparison and subjective.\n[/list]\n[h1]Conclusion[/h1]\n\nNormally I hate fanboys of an original game that bash the sequel just because it wasn't more of the same. Sequels have to try something new in order to distinguish themselves from the original and trying something new is often alienating for the previous fan base (people hate change). So normally I like to appreciate a sequel on its own merits and there are definitely some nice new ideas in this game, but I feel that the problem with this game is that it traded its fundamental game mechanics and gameplay proposition (pretty much its soul) for the sake of having a sequel at all. Some of the new ideas worked, some didn't, but the real meat of the game (the food prep) has just gotten way too lifeless compared to the original. Props all the same to the developer for being a one man band but I don't hold out much hope of this game improving without a fundamental overhaul of the entire food preparation elements from the ground up. There's too much on the menu that's too much the same and the lack of the way preparation progression worked like in the original really holds back the feeling of getting better in amongst the manic food serving.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505660665