t's not even counting the campaign mode, which is currently unfocused but has wide latitude for the customization of your restaurant.\n\nYou play the role of a chef, with the basic gameplay being the completion of orders from customers and various chores throughout a working day.  Chore tasks have a time fixed set of inputs based on chore type, however most food items are cooked to order, so you will have to check the bottom of the screen to figure out what to do.  On paper every kind of food is straightforward if you follow the recipe faithfully, but if you want to cook at lightning speed each food is essentially a different minigame to master.  Once things get serious you need accurate execution and quick thinking to succeed.\n\nWhile the core gameplay above is the same as in the first game, this game has added extra depth to the system beyond the stunning number of foods.  This game adds the feature of 4-8 holding stations (at the top of the screen) you can use to prepare food ahead of time, especially useful during the lulls before and between rush hours.  This includes some of the entrees as well as side dishes, which are a new gameplay element. Holding stations can be used for side dishes or a subset of entrees. In short, the situation might call for different strategy, which deepens the already busy moment-to-moment gameplay of prioritization.  \n\nThere are major changes to the campaign.  In both games you are in charge of your own restaurant, responsible for setting a menu and purchasing ingredients from your profits.  The second game adds in a new game mode called 'Chef for Hire', where you do shifts at other restaurants.  The previous game's checklist of requirements to earn stars for your restaurant has been replaced simply by the need to gain experience, which can be done in both game modes.  You can now unlock decor for your restaurant  and some new foods either by gaining levels, getting medals in the 'Chef for Hire' levels, or by completing various milestones in your restaurant.  I confess that I had a surprising amount of fun messing around with the restaurant designer after I had earned a number of unlocks.\n\nI have been fairly detailed in the changes to the campaign since it's probably the most controversial part of the changes.  The campaign mode in the first game had a number of issues.  For instance, the checklist to gain stars required playing a certain number of days, which if you were doing well felt like a pointless grind.  There were also a greater variety of upgrades you could purchase, in addition to having to level up your foods to increase their sale price and adding complexity to their recipes.  My view is that while the chore reduction upgrades are popular, the game as it stands is better off without them: juggling chores is a core part of gameplay, and gives teeth to the food modifiers that increase the trash or dishes produced. \n\nUnfortunately, the changes to the campaign have their drawbacks. In the new game the only way you invest in your restaurant is by buying dishes, and once you've bought a dish you don't have to upgrade it any further.  Unless you are prone to experimenting thoroughly in menu design, this means that money becomes basically useless fairly quickly.  I think now that level advancement isn't tied soley to the main restaurant, players don't really have the same emotional connection with the progress of 'their' restaurant.  It's currently not hard to gain stars by playing 'chef for hire' levels exclusively.  There might also be an issue that without food upgrades a new player might easily set up a menu that is unreasonably complicated, whereas in the first game that was generally avoided by having artifical barriers to obtaining complicated foods.  I will note that the developer has noted feedback about the campaign, and has announced that he intends to offer improvents in a future update.\n\nIt would be remiss of me to not mention that several other issues remain with the game at the current time, due to bugs that cropped up late in the development cycle.  Food modifiers are currently hidden from the player, and a system of emails similar to the first game is currently disabled (the lack of emails might be a contributing cause to the lack of player attachment to the main campaign mode).  I am personally optimistic in the developer's ability to fix these, but am aware that my review should address the game as it currently stands.  For this reason, I had initially planned to put off my review until after after a few patches, but I'm honestly having way too much fun with the game as it stands right now to give anything but a thumbs up.\n\nIn conclusion, if you have any interest in the high-tension gameplay then this game is absolutely a must-buy right now.  If your primary interest is in the feeling of progress building a successful restaurant from scratch, then I would say that you should wait and see for changes to the campaign system.  The game currently gives you a very wide ability to customize your restaurant through menu selection and decor, but that sense of progress just isn't there right now.  However, the chef for hire levels alone are worth the price of entry, and the game has a staggering amount of content in its current form.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505879823, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1505879823, "recommendationid": "35077165", "language": "english", "votes_down": 5, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.534128", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1507106008, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 306, "num_reviews": 3, "playtime_forever": 1729, "steamid": "76561198124734781", "num_games_owned": 48}, "votes_funny": 1, "votes_up": 28, "comment_count": "2", "review": "I've enjoyed playing this game, but I do not find it as fun as the first one was. I loved the emails, the catering, and the overall story you had in the first one. I enjoyed upgrading fo