urant together.  I get this order, you get that one.  I'll do these chores, you prep the holding stations.  Everything feels so natural and flushed out that I honestly can't even play single player anymore.  It's also just not as fun for me to do everything by myself either.  That's a sign that a game has a good multiplayer.\n\n\nAnd now that I've spent far too long bragging on all the things about this game I like, there are a few things that I want to highlight that I feel could've been done better.\n\n1. The Level System\nThe level system is a neat addon that I really like - however, the biggest criticism I have of it is that it just doesn't feel like it really means anything.  Sure, you get customization rewards for levelling up, but you also get them for completing days at almost any restaurant in the game and for earning milestones.  Sure, you get new stars for your restaurant, but that really doesn't have any significant effect outside of earning new holding areas and prep stations to make your own restaurant a worthwhile challenge.  At the end of the day, the level system just feels like more of a tracker for how much you've played the game and doesn't really warrant any of the things we crave for earning higher levels (most namely bragging rights).\n\n2. Your Own Restaurant\nMost of the people I've seen play this game (and myself included) almost exclusively tend to focus more on the alternative restaurants in the game than on their own.  Customization aside, there isn't really any benefit to playing in your own restaurant.  I keep thinking that its weird how levelling up increases your Star Rating for your restaurant.  How does doing a week's worth of cooking in Max Weiners make my restaurant look good? (#ROASTED!  Sorry Max Weiners I still love you and your hilarious name)  Then again, if you're the most renound chef at XLR Purple then people may hold your own restaurant to a minimum standard.  At the end of the day, having your own restaurant is basically just a glorified sandbox - which is nice, don't get me wrong - but a bit underwhelming considering that the first game made it such a big deal.\n\n3. Food Upgrades\nWait, what food upgrades?  Oh, right.  It kinda bothers me that this game completely got rid of one of the biggest mechanics from the original - all the foods are as is from day 1.  Understandably it would make a TON of extra work to include 3-5 upgrades for each of the 186 food items currently in the game.  Still, I can't help but miss my favorite foods getting progressively more stressful to make as the game gets harder and harder with no remorse.  It's part of the Cook, Serve, Delicious charm.\n\n4. Realism / Lack of Gameplay Variety\nWhile this isn't necessarily something that's wrong with the game, it does feel like a really big missed opportunity.  These two headers are coupled together because they're both raised by a single point.  Being able to play in a bunch of different restaurants is awesome and enjoyable, but at the end of the day, they're all too similar.  Sure, different menus and different food styles vary up all the different locations enough for them to pull their own weight, but they're all more or less the same challenge with slightly different button combinations.  To expand on this, as you would expect you'll always see a rush hour at noon and another one at dinnertime.  For most restaurants this is expected.  But why are so many people in Breakfast & Breakloose ordering cereal and pancakes at 12:30pm?  I mean, I like to sleep in as much as the next food patron, but you'd think a breakfast joint would have a rush hour much earlier in the day, right?  And this is the missed opportunity I brought up.  Instead of the same day with a different menu, each restaurant could have different rush hour times and operating hours.  Sure a breakfast restaurant may be easier to work at than a bar with literally All The Sports, but are you prepared to handle a Rush Hour at 8am?  I feel like this kind of realism can add a new prospect for the game's challenges - that just like in real life, all restaurants have different rushes and slow periods.  They also have different hours, too.  This dessert place has an adorable mascot, but it doesn't really feel like most people would be swarming to get a bowl of ice cream at 9am in the morning.  Then again, who am I kidding?  I'd eat a bowl of ice cream any time of day.\n\n\nBecause of Review length limits, I'm going to have to stop here.  Overall I would certainly recommend this game if you enjoyed the first one.  Feel free to leave your own opinions about things that were done well and/or things that could've been better.  Please be respectful and polite, and if you offer criticism please make sure it's constructive.\n\nOverall, I rate Cook, Serve, Delicious! 2!! as 7.5/10.  Thanks for reading!", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1506629928, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1506629928, "recommendationid": "35271366", "language": "english", "votes_down": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.517380", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1506317187, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 1013, "num_reviews": 4, "playtime_forever": 2170, "steamid": "76561198070196264", "num_games_owned": 156}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 9, "comment_count": 0, "review": "I can and will probably play this game to death. Some of the later levels in restaurants are crazy hard! If you like a challenge and multitasking, pick this up!\n\nThere are a lot of pros and cons that go along with this review, but the majority of cons will boil down to content that made the first CSD great that has not made its way in yet.\n\nShould this have been more of an early access release? Yes. Am I mad it wasn't? Absolutely not. Does it miss that story charm from the first one? Of course (but it will eventually be implemented).\n\nAs far as I'm concerned, I would've purchased this either way, and it's k